# Paco Syntactic Grammar (EBNF)

> Status: **complete** — all foundational design decisions settled (see
> `docs/design/decisions/`). This grammar is the normative syntactic reference;
> `docs/grammar/tokens.md` is the normative lexical reference.

## EBNF Notation

| Form | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `Production = Expression ;` | Definition of a production rule |
| `a \| b` | Alternation — either `a` or `b` |
| `a b` | Concatenation — `a` followed by `b` |
| `[ a ]` | Option — 0 or 1 occurrence of `a` |
| `{ a }` | Repetition — 0 or more occurrences of `a` |
| `( a )` | Grouping |
| `"terminal"` | Literal terminal string |
| `(* comment *)` | Informal comment |

Terminals written in **CamelCase** (e.g., `Identifier`, `Literal`) are defined
in `docs/grammar/tokens.md`. All other terminals are quoted strings.

---

## 1. Program and Top-Level Items

A source file is a sequence of *attributed items*. An outer attribute applies to
the item that immediately follows it.

```ebnf
Program = { AttributedItem } ;

AttributedItem = { OuterAttribute } Item ;

Item = FunctionDecl
     | StructDecl
     | EnumDecl
     | TraitDecl
     | MethodsBlock
     | UseDecl ;

(* @test  @derive(Display, Clone)  @allow("lint-code") *)
OuterAttribute = "@" Identifier [ "(" [ AttributeArgList ] ")" ] ;

AttributeArgList = AttributeArg { "," AttributeArg } [ "," ] ;

AttributeArg = Literal | Path | Identifier | OuterAttribute ;

(* use std::io  |  use "github.com/user/json" *)
UseDecl = "use" ( Path | StringLiteral ) [ ";" ] ;
```

---

## 2. Declarations and Signatures

```ebnf
(* Covers: fn, iter fn, comptime fn *)
FunctionDecl = [ "comptime" | "iter" ] "fn" Identifier
               [ GenericParams ] Signature [ BlockExpr ] ;

Signature = "(" [ ParameterList ] ")" [ "->" Type ] ;

ParameterList = Receiver [ "," ]
              | Receiver "," Parameter { "," Parameter } [ "," ]
              | Parameter { "," Parameter } [ "," ] ;

(* self     → move (consumes the value)
   self&    → shared borrow (read-only, the common case)
   self&mut → mutable borrow *)
Receiver = "self" [ "&" | "&mut" ] ;

Parameter = Identifier ":" Type ;
```

### Struct and enum

```ebnf
StructDecl = "struct" Identifier [ GenericParams ] [ WhereClause ]
             "{" { StructMember } "}" ;

(* Methods defined inside the struct block (ADR 0002) *)
StructMember = { OuterAttribute } ( StructField | FunctionDecl ) ;

StructField = Identifier ":" Type [ "," ] ;

EnumDecl = "enum" Identifier [ GenericParams ] [ WhereClause ]
           "{" { EnumMember } "}" ;

(* Methods may also be defined inside the enum block (ADR 0002) *)
EnumMember = { OuterAttribute } ( EnumVariant | FunctionDecl ) ;

EnumVariant = Identifier [ "(" [ VariantFieldList ] ")" ] [ "," ] ;

VariantFieldList = VariantField { "," VariantField } [ "," ] ;

(* Named: Circle(radius: f64)   Unnamed: Pair(f64, f64) *)
VariantField = [ Identifier ":" ] Type ;
```

### Trait and extension block

```ebnf
TraitDecl = "trait" Identifier [ GenericParams ] [ WhereClause ]
            "{" { TraitMember } "}" ;

TraitMember = { OuterAttribute } TraitFunctionDecl ;

(* Trait methods may omit the body (abstract) or include a default body *)
TraitFunctionDecl = "fn" Identifier [ GenericParams ] Signature
                    ( BlockExpr | ";" ) ;

(* Extend a type defined in another module (ADR 0002).
   Example:  methods String { fn trim(self&) -> &string { ... } } *)
MethodsBlock = "methods" [ GenericParams ] Type [ WhereClause ]
               "{" { { OuterAttribute } FunctionDecl } "}" ;
```

### Generics and bounds

```ebnf
GenericParams = "<" GenericParam { "," GenericParam } [ "," ] ">" ;

(* Type parameter with optional trait bound:  T  |  T: Display + Clone *)
GenericParam = Lifetime | Identifier [ ":" TraitBoundList ] ;

WhereClause = "where" WhereBound { "," WhereBound } [ "," ] ;

WhereBound = ( Lifetime | Type ) ":" TraitBoundList ;

TraitBoundList = TraitBound { "+" TraitBound } ;

TraitBound = [ "?" ] ( Path | GenericType ) ;
```

---

## 3. Type System

```ebnf
Type = PrimitiveType
     | BorrowType
     | ArrayType
     | SliceType
     | TupleType
     | DynType
     | FnType
     | GenericType
     | Path ;          (* user-defined or imported type *)

PrimitiveType = "i8"  | "i16" | "i32" | "i64"
              | "u8"  | "u16" | "u32" | "u64"
              | "int" | "uint"
              | "f32" | "f64"
              | "bool" | "char" | "string" | "byte" | "type" ;

(* &T   &mut T   &'a T   &'a mut T *)
BorrowType = "&" [ Lifetime [ "mut" ] ] Type | "&mut" Type ;

(* [Type; Size] — e.g. [int; 64] *)
ArrayType = "[" Type ";" IntegerLiteral "]" ;

(* []byte   []int   []string *)
SliceType = "[" "]" Type ;

(* (int, string)   (f64, f64, f64) *)
TupleType = "(" Type "," Type { "," Type } [ "," ] ")" ;

(* dyn Sink   dyn Iterator<Item = int> — dynamic dispatch, visible vtable cost *)
DynType = "dyn" ( Path | GenericType ) ;

(* fn(int, string) -> bool — function type for higher-order parameters *)
FnType = "fn" "(" [ TypeList ] ")" [ "->" Type ] ;

(* Vec<T>   Result<T, E>   Map<string, int> *)
GenericType = Path "<" TypeList ">" ;

TypeList = TypeOrBinding { "," TypeOrBinding } [ "," ] ;

TypeOrBinding = [ Identifier "=" ] Type ;

(* Module-qualified paths:  std::io::Error   Option   Vec *)
Path = Identifier { "::" Identifier } ;
```

---

## 4. Statements

Semicolons are optional terminators (not mandatory separators).

```ebnf
Statement = LetStmt
          | ExprStmt
          | ";" ;

(* let x = 10       let mut y: int = 20
   let (a, b) = pair    let Some(v) = opt *)
LetStmt = "let" [ "mut" ] Pattern [ ":" Type ] [ "=" Expr ] [ ";" ] ;

ExprStmt = Expr [ ";" ] ;
```

---

## 5. Expressions and Control Flow

Operator precedence is encoded in the grammar hierarchy, from lowest (top) to
highest (bottom). Each level passes through to the next.

```ebnf
Expr = AssignmentExpr ;

(* Right-associative: x = y = z *)
AssignmentExpr = LogicalOrExpr
               [ ( "=" | "+=" | "-=" | "*=" | "/=" | "%=" ) Expr ] ;

LogicalOrExpr  = LogicalAndExpr  { "||"  LogicalAndExpr  } ;
LogicalAndExpr = BitwiseOrExpr   { "&&"  BitwiseOrExpr   } ;
BitwiseOrExpr  = BitwiseXorExpr  { "|"   BitwiseXorExpr  } ;
BitwiseXorExpr = BitwiseAndExpr  { "^"   BitwiseAndExpr  } ;
BitwiseAndExpr = ComparisonExpr  { "&"   ComparisonExpr  } ;

(* Non-associative: a == b == c is a parse error *)
ComparisonExpr = ShiftExpr
               [ ( "==" | "!=" | "<" | "<=" | ">" | ">=" ) ShiftExpr ] ;

ShiftExpr      = RangeExpr       { ( "<<" | ">>" ) RangeExpr      } ;

(* Non-associative: 1..10..20 is a parse error *)
RangeExpr      = AdditiveExpr    [ ( ".." | "..=" ) AdditiveExpr  ] ;

AdditiveExpr       = MultiplicativeExpr { ( "+" | "-" ) MultiplicativeExpr } ;
MultiplicativeExpr = CastExpr           { ( "*" | "/" | "%" ) CastExpr     } ;

(* expr as Type — left-associative, higher precedence than arithmetic *)
CastExpr = UnaryExpr { "as" Type } ;

(* Prefix unary operators and borrow.
   Note: & here is borrow, not bitwise-and (which is infix in BitwiseAndExpr). *)
UnaryExpr = ( "-" | "!" | "~" | "&" [ "mut" ] | "&mut" | "*" ) UnaryExpr
          | SpawnExpr
          | PostfixExpr ;

(* spawn expr    spawn { ... }    let h = spawn risky() *)
SpawnExpr = "spawn" ( BlockExpr | UnaryExpr ) ;

(* Postfix operators: method call, field access, index, call, propagation *)
PostfixExpr = AtomExpr { PostfixOp } ;

PostfixOp =
    (* Generic method call: expr.collect<Vec<int>>()
       Note: parser disambiguates "<" from less-than by lookahead. *)
    "." Identifier "<" TypeList ">" "(" [ ArgList ] ")"
    (* Plain method call: expr.push(x) *)
  | "." Identifier "(" [ ArgList ] ")"
    (* Field access: point.x *)
  | "." Identifier
    (* Index on slices and arrays. NOT valid on strings (ADR 0010). *)
  | "[" Expr "]"
    (* Free call: f(x, y) *)
  | "(" [ ArgList ] ")"
    (* Error/absence propagation: result?  option? *)
  | "?" ;

AtomExpr = Literal
         | ClosureExpr
         | StructInitExpr
         | PathExpr
         | TupleExpr
         | SliceExpr
         | BlockExpr
         | ControlFlowExpr
         | "(" Expr ")" ;

(* Type-qualified path with optional generic turbofish:
   Vec::new()    Option::Some(1)    path::to::fn::<T>() *)
PathExpr = Path [ "::" "<" TypeList ">" ] ;

(* Struct initializer: Config { host: "x", port: 8080 }
   Note: not allowed as the expression of `if`/`while`/`for` to avoid
   ambiguity with block expressions — resolved in the parser, not here. *)
StructInitExpr = Path "{" [ StructInitFieldList ] "}" ;

StructInitFieldList = StructInitField { "," StructInitField } [ "," ] ;

(* field: expr  — or shorthand  field  (when variable name matches field name) *)
StructInitField = Identifier [ ":" Expr ] ;

(* (a, b, c)   ()  — also used for grouping when containing a single expression *)
TupleExpr = "(" [ ExprList ] ")" ;

(* [1, 2, 3]   []   [0; 64] — the last form fills 64 elements with 0 *)
SliceExpr = "[" [ ExprList ] "]"
          | "[" Expr ";" Expr "]" ;

ExprList = Expr { "," Expr } [ "," ] ;

ArgList = Arg { "," Arg } [ "," ] ;

(* Named argument:  capacity: 8    — or positional *)
Arg = [ Identifier ":" ] Expr ;

(* Closures: |x| x + 1   |x: int, y: int| { x + y }   || { ... } *)
ClosureExpr = "|" [ ClosureParamList ] "|" ( BlockExpr | Expr ) ;

ClosureParamList = ClosureParam { "," ClosureParam } [ "," ] ;

ClosureParam = Pattern [ ":" Type ] ;

(* Block: { stmts... [tail_expr] }
   The optional trailing expression is the block's value (no semicolon). *)
BlockExpr = "{" { Statement } [ Expr ] "}" ;
```

### Control flow

```ebnf
ControlFlowExpr = IfExpr
                | MatchExpr
                | WhileExpr
                | ForExpr
                | LoopExpr
                | SelectExpr
                | YieldExpr
                | ReturnExpr
                | BreakExpr
                | ContinueExpr
                | ComptimeExpr ;

(* if cond { }   if cond { } else { }   if let pat = expr { } *)
IfExpr = "if" [ "let" Pattern "=" ] Expr BlockExpr
         [ "else" ( BlockExpr | IfExpr ) ] ;

(* Exhaustive: the compiler rejects non-exhaustive match arms *)
MatchExpr = "match" Expr "{" { MatchArm } "}" ;

MatchArm = Pattern [ "if" Expr ] "=>" Expr [ "," ] ;

WhileExpr = "while" [ "let" Pattern "=" ] Expr BlockExpr ;

ForExpr = "for" Pattern "in" Expr BlockExpr ;

LoopExpr = "loop" BlockExpr ;

(* select {
       v = rx1.recv() => handle(v),
       timeout(1s)    => log("timeout"),
   } *)
SelectExpr = "select" "{" { SelectArm } "}" ;

(* Binding form: identifier = channel_expr => handler
   Plain form:   timeout_expr => handler             *)
SelectArm = [ Identifier "=" ] Expr "=>" Expr [ "," ]
          | "default" "=>" Expr [ "," ] ;

(* Only valid inside `iter fn` blocks — see ADR 0004 / spec §8 *)
YieldExpr = "yield" Expr ;

ReturnExpr = "return" [ Expr ] ;

(* break with an optional value (for loop-as-expression) *)
BreakExpr = "break" [ Expr ] ;

ContinueExpr = "continue" ;

(* comptime { ... }   or   comptime expr *)
ComptimeExpr = "comptime" ( BlockExpr | Expr ) ;
```

---

## 6. Patterns

Patterns appear in `match` arms, `let` bindings, `if let`, `while let`, and
closure/function parameters. They are matched top-to-bottom; the first
alternative that fits the syntactic context is used. Semantic disambiguation
(e.g., identifier-as-binding vs. unit enum variant) is done by the resolver.

```ebnf
Pattern = WildcardPattern
        | LiteralPattern
        | BindingPattern
        | ReferencePattern
        | TuplePattern
        | SlicePattern
        | RangePattern
        | NamedPattern ;
```

### Individual pattern forms

```ebnf
(* _ — matches anything and discards the value *)
WildcardPattern = "_" ;

(* -42   3.14   "hello"   true   'x' *)
LiteralPattern = [ "-" ] Literal ;

(* [mut] name @ sub_pattern — bind the matched value to `name`.
   Example:  n @ 1..=9 => ...   |   c @ Shape::Circle(_) => ...
   Parser tries this before NamedPattern when `@` follows the identifier. *)
BindingPattern = [ "mut" ] Identifier "@" Pattern ;

(* &pat   &mut pat — match through a reference *)
ReferencePattern = ( "&" [ "mut" ] | "&mut" ) Pattern ;

(* (a, b)   (x, _, z) *)
TuplePattern = "(" [ PatternList ] ")" ;

(* [head, tail @ ..]   [a, b, c] *)
SlicePattern = "[" [ PatternList ] "]" ;

(* 1..=9   'a'..='z'   ..=100 *)
RangePattern = [ LiteralPattern ] ( ".." | "..=" ) [ LiteralPattern ] ;

(* Covers four overlapping forms resolved by the resolver:
     - Bare identifier binding:     x          (no "::", no parens)
     - Mutable binding:             mut x
     - Unit variant:                Option::None
     - Tuple variant:               Some(x)   Shape::Circle(r)
     - Struct variant:              Point { x, y }
   When the path contains "::", it is always a type path, not a local binding. *)
NamedPattern = [ "mut" ] Path
               [ "(" [ PatternList ] ")"
               | "{" [ StructPatternFieldList ] [ ".." ] "}" ] ;

PatternList = Pattern { "," Pattern } [ "," ] ;

StructPatternFieldList = StructPatternField { "," StructPatternField } [ "," ] ;

(* field: pat  — or shorthand  field  (binds field name as variable) *)
StructPatternField = Identifier [ ":" Pattern ] ;
```

---

## 7. Lexical Terminals

The terminals below are defined in `docs/grammar/tokens.md`. This section
summarizes them for cross-reference only.

```ebnf
Identifier = (* [A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*  — not a keyword *) ;

Lifetime   = (* "'" Identifier  — e.g. 'a  'static *) ;

Literal    = IntegerLiteral
           | FloatLiteral
           | StringLiteral
           | CharLiteral
           | BoolLiteral ;

IntegerLiteral = (* 42  1_000  0xFF  0b1010 *) ;
FloatLiteral   = (* 3.14  1.0e9 *) ;
StringLiteral  = (* "UTF-8 text" with \n \t \r \" \\ escapes *) ;
CharLiteral    = (* 'a'  '\n' *) ;
BoolLiteral    = "true" | "false" ;
```

---

## 8. Known Ambiguities and Parser Notes

The following ambiguities are real; they are resolved by the parser using
lookahead, not by restructuring the grammar:

| Ambiguity | Resolution |
|-----------|------------|
| `f < g > h` — comparison vs. generic call | If `f` names a known type/function with generic params, treat `<` as opening a type list; otherwise treat as less-than. |
| `expr.method<T>(args)` — generic method vs. comparison | After `.identifier`, if `<` is followed by a type-list then `)`, treat as generic call. |
| `Foo { ... }` — struct init vs. block | Struct initializers are disallowed as the direct expression of `if`/`while`/`for` conditions; a parenthesized form `(Foo { ... })` is used instead. |
| `Identifier` in pattern — binding vs. unit variant | Resolved by the name resolver: if the path resolves to a value in the type namespace, it is a variant; otherwise it is a new binding. |
| `{ }` — block expression vs. struct init | Struct init requires a preceding `Path`; a bare `{` always opens a block. |
